One of the first tasks set by the UNFCCC was for signatory nations to establish national greenhouse gas inventories of greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions and removals, which were used to create the 1990 benchmark levels for accession of Annex I countries to the Kyoto Protocol and for
The Protocol was amended in 2012 to encompass the second one for the period 2013‚Äì2020 in the Doha Amendment.[16]

The 2010 United Nations Climate Change Conference produced an agreement stating that future global warming should be limited to below 2 ¬∞C (3.6 ¬∞F) relative to the pre-industrial level.[15] The Kyoto Protocol had two commitment periods, the first of which lasted from 2008 to 2012
The Kyoto Protocol was concluded and established legally binding obligations under international law, for developed countries to reduce their greenhouse gas emissions in the period 2008‚Äì2012.[6]

The 1st Conference of the Parties (COP-1) decided that the aim of Annex I Parties stabilizing their emissions at 1990 levels by 2000 was "not adequate",[14] and further discussions at later conferences led to the Kyoto Protocol in 1997.

This was a hard one to write, no happy ending. But please read and share to raise more awareness of how climate change a problem caused BY HUMANS (fossil fuels, cutting down forests and farming for meat) impacts other creatures that really don't deserve it https://t.co/n9AEbND6El
And I was serious when I said a few months back that I want to be bringing more awareness about animal stories in Asia -- there are plenty https://t.co/QYEtyUMoJM

With all the news of the Yangtze drying up due to the heatwave and lesser rain, I thought about the animals. They're almost always never considered and I felt it was impt to highlight (and so obvious) https://t.co/n9AEbND6El

Sharing my thought process in coming up with the idea for this piece: It was really an observation I had (I think my best works are a result of my overthinking). At CNN digital at least we've been covering the climate crisis across Asia quite fiercely...  https://t.co/EtwZN4kEQi

Full quote from Sam: "We look at dinosaurs and dodos and almost expect extinction as something inevitable; it's not and shouldn't be. Extinction is forever. We can't take it lightly." "This is the sort of complacency that allowed the Yangtze River dolphin to disappear."

(On that note, I don't get or trust experts who still want to be hopeful or positive when things are already reaching breaking point. Why? It's really a case of act blur, live longer -- plus points if you get Singlish)

There's always that magic 'teaching moment' you get when you do good interviews with great sources. Sam was one -- he talked about the complacency of people in general and how we have become so desensitized as a society when it comes to climate change and extinction.

"Although they are a protected species, Chinese giant salamanders are under greater threat from climate change - increasing global temperatures and droughts definitely do it no good when it is already extremely vulnerable. Their chances of survival become drastically thin." (3/3)

Sam Turvey, dedicated conservationist and zoologist (fyi he was the man who chased down the last Yangtze river dolphin): "Giant salamanders only live within freshwater environments. Lower water levels would inevitably place greater pressure on their numbers across China." (2/3)

There are so many animals in danger as China continues to grapple with its record heatwave and drought. But I wanted to highlight these guys in particular: Chinese giant salamanders. Considered to be living fossils and now subjected to so much danger. Quite infuriating. (1/3) https://t.co/Rpg5lD9cqQ

Other animals that call the Yangtze home: finless porpoises, several species of turtle like this Yangtze giant softshell turtle pictured in a local zoo. Couldn't find any licensed photos of ones in the wild which says A LOT. (Right?) https://t.co/cYUeI67Euk

Context I got from researchers at WWF China: "Reduced river flow and warmer waters in the Yangtze are a threat to freshwater species and increase pressure on already critically endangered animals like the remaining Chinese alligators left in the wild." https://t.co/n9AEbND6El

First up is the Chinese alligator, listed as critically endangered by the IUCN. It only lives in freshwater and has been part of Chinese literature for centuries. It numbers in the wild have dropped due to habitat loss. Add climate change to the mix and things don't look good. https://t.co/DaBwtIlGZ2
